dev.foxgirl.rembulan

Class Ordering.NumericOrdering

  • java.lang.Object
    • dev.foxgirl.rembulan.Ordering<Number>
      • dev.foxgirl.rembulan.Ordering.NumericOrdering
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Comparator<Number>
    Enclosing class:
    Ordering<T>

    public static final class Ordering.NumericOrdering
extends Ordering<Number>
    Numeric ordering.

    Numbers are compared using the comparison methods provided by LuaMathOperators, defining the ordering as one based on the ordering of the mathematical values of the numbers in question.

    This class implements the Comparator interface by imposing a total order on numbers that differs from the ordering defined by the methods eq(Number, Number), lt(Number, Number) and le(Number, Number):

    • NaN is treated as equal to itself and greater than any other number, while eq(a, b) == false and lt(a, b) == false when a or b is NaN;
    • -0.0 is considered to be lesser than 0.0, while eq(-0.0, 0.0) == true and lt(-0.0, 0.0) == false.

    Note that the total ordering imposed by the compare(Number, Number) is inconsistent with equals.

    For proper treatment of NaNs and (float) zero values, use the Ordering methods directly.

      • compare

        public int compare(Number a,
                   Number b)
        Compare the numbers a and b, yielding an integer that is negative, zero or positive if a is lesser than, equal to, or greater than b.

        The ordering imposed by this method differs from the one defined by the methods eq(Number, Number), lt(Number, Number) and le(Number, Number) in the treatment of NaNs and float zeros:

        • NaN is treated as equal to itself and greater than any other number, while eq(a, b) == false and lt(a, b) == false when a or b is NaN;
        • -0.0 is considered to be lesser than 0.0, while eq(-0.0, 0.0) == true and lt(-0.0, 0.0) == false.

        The total ordering of Number objects imposed by this method is inconsistent with equals.

        Parameters:
        a - first argument, must not be null
        b - second argument, must not be null
        Returns:
        a negative, zero or positive integer if the number a is lesser than, equal to, or greater than the number b
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if a or b is null
